HEADWORD: Dodecahedron
<hw>Do*dec`a*he"dron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/
twelve + <?/ seat, bottom, base: cf. F.
<ets>dod⟦eacute⟧ca⟦egrave⟧dre</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Geom. &
Crystallog.)</fld> <def>A solid having twelve faces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>regular dodecahedron</xex> is bounded by twelve
equal and regular pentagons; the pyritohedron (see
<er>Pyritohedron</er>) is related to it; the <xex>rhombic
dodecahedron</xex> is bounded by twelve equal rhombic faces.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

